write a Terraform configuration provisioning an EC2 t2.micro instance on AWS in eu-west-1 with an S3 remote backend, then run terraform plan and terraform apply
Steps
1
Open your terminal. If Terraform is not installed, go to developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install first.
You will see: Your terminal prompt
2
In your GitHub repository, navigate to the /terraform/ folder. Create main.tf with: provider 'aws' block (region = eu-west-1), aws_vpc resource, aws_subnet resource, aws_internet_gateway, aws_security_group (ports 22 and 80), and aws_instance resource (ami = ami-0694d931cee176e7d for eu-west-1 Amazon Linux 2, instance_type = t2.micro).
You will see: main.tf file created in your editor

3
Create backend.tf with an S3 backend block. Choose a bucket name like nexacloud-tf-state-[your-initials]-2025. Create this bucket in AWS S3 first (same region, versioning enabled), then reference it in backend.tf.

You will see: backend.tf with your S3 bucket name

4
Run: terraform init. This downloads the AWS provider and connects to your S3 backend.

You will see: Terraform has been successfully initialized

5
Run: terraform plan. Read the output carefully — it should show resources to add with no errors.

You will see: Plan: N to add, 0 to change, 0 to destroy

6
Run: terraform apply and type yes when prompted. Wait for completion.

You will see: Apply complete! Resources: N added

7
Copy your EC2 instance ID from the apply output or from the AWS Console (EC2 → Instances). It starts with i-0 and is 17 characters long. Paste it into your submission.

You will see: Instance ID in format: i-0xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
solution
1. AWS configure
Get AWS Access keys:Log in to AWS Console → https://console.aws.amazon.comClick your username top-right → Security credentialsScroll to "Access keys" section → Click Create access keyChoose use case: Select Command Line Interface CLI if you’re using Terraform/CLI. Click NextDescription tag: Optional, e.g. terraform-laptop. Click Create access keyCopy both keys now:Access key ID = AKIA... 20 charsSecret access key = long random stringImportant: You can only see the Secret key once. Click Download.csv file to save it, or copy/paste immediately. If you lose it, you’ll have to create a new key.
2. Create S3 bucket for remote state firstTerraform needs the bucket to exist before init. Run once:bashaws s3api create-bucket \
  --bucket nexacloud-tf-state-ab-2026 \
  --region eu-west-1 \
  --create-bucket-configuration LocationConstraint=eu-west-1

aws s3api put-bucket-versioning \
  --bucket nexacloud-tf-state-ab-2026 \
  --versioning-configuration Status=EnabledReplace ab with your initials. Bucket names must be globally unique.
3.Create /terraform/ folder + filesbashmkdir terraform && cd terraform
4.nano main.tf to create a mani.tf file in your terraform folder
5.Terraform init
6. Terraform plan
7. Terraform apply
8. Terraform destroy to destroy the infrastructure.

Good. Infrastructure is in place.

